tion of the world that produced and used it. Her work reveals the continuing importance of pagan festivals and cults in the Christian era and highlights the rise of a respectable aristocratic Christianity that combined pagan and Christian practices. Salzman stresses the key role of the Christian emperors and imperial institutions in supporting pagan rituals. Such policies of accomodation and assimilation resulted in a gradual and relatively peaceful transformation of Rome from a pagan to a Christian capital.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520909106423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520909106.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles